<font color="#FF0000">AND ALL THAT TRAINING WAS </font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 29  0:56:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John;<br>
What you write about, was,  I am now beginning to understand true about Army units and how they operated in Vietnam. It was not necessary so, of the Marine Corps and what we engaged in, at least when I was there.<br>
While what I posted above is true, that we were trained to fight a conventional war, but found ourselves in the midst of guerrilla welfare without a front line, fighting a type of war we were not trained to pursue, we were also not trained for manning defensive fighting positions. A Marine building defensive fighting positions such as bunkers was unheard of before Vietnam. I found it strange that we did so. It was not the Marine Corps way, we were trained to fight and to go after the enemy and fight on until we either killed them or he killed us and we were prepared to fight all the way to Hanoi if we were told and allowed too.<br><br>
What we could not understand was all the rules and regulations. What type of war is it where you give the enemy a day off so that he can get re-supplied? Take out his dead yes, care for his wounded yes, but to allow do gooders the opportunity to trade and supply the enemy with medical and food supplies that I could not understand. <br>
We were also not prepared for the long waits that followed in between the battles. We could not understand that and neither could our platoon leaders.  <br>
At first we were told we would be fighting Viet Cong but I saw only a few of them during my tour of duty and can count the times we engaged them in battle. We were also told that the Viet Cong would not stand and fight and this is true of the Viet Cong, but what we encountered was not the Viet Cong. <br>
Instead we fought hard core well trained and well disciplined Communist forces. They, the NVA we found out were a worthy foe to engage in battle.<br><br>
But it was a surprise to our own commanding officers that it was NVA we found ourselves engaging in battle. So all the training and tactics of battle we had been prepared for we found useless there. What did occur was that at the small unit level there was no absence of leadership and squad leaders often improvised and by some miraculous ways we seemed to survive against over whelming odds. <br>
At the same time, I honestly believe that the North Vietnamese officers operating in our area loved to engage Marines in battle especially in small unit size operations as this provided them the experience they desired to obtain and to prove themselves in battle. <br>
The same may be true on our side, think about it, every 6 months a new 2nd Louie would be send in so that he could earn his medals and gain his own personal combat experiences that would look good for his career in the Corps. Often small unit were send out as bait to attract  the enemy, but just as often some one almost always failed to prepare the supplies and reactionary force we would need once contact was made. <br><br>
I remember often while being pinned down out in the open, while all types of incoming was going on, I would just roll over on my back and light up a cigarette and wait. Its funny now to think about it, but there,  I was puffing away while bullets blazed overhead.  There was not much else one could do. <br>
We also hated having to pay twice for the same real estate but this we often did, allowing the gooks to process the site by night while we patrolled the area by day. There were too many rules we were forced to follow while nobody evidently told the enemy they were suppose to follow those same rules. <br><br>
Still, we did form our own killer teams and sought out the enemy in their secured areas and unfortunately all too often paid a high price for our efforts.  <br><br>
We did not work at all with the South Vietnamese Army, we didn’t trust them. Those that were assigned to our CAC units (pacification program where a squad of Marines lived among the villagers along with a south Vietnamese popular force of about 30-40 soldiers), we often found we had shot on the other side of the fence during night attacks, what a war. <br>
That is why I believe we will never again fight that type of war. Technology has made those types of battles obsolete. The last real battles were fought were in Vietnam and it’s a lost art by today’s standards. The only other time we will fight that type of combat again will be after the nuclear war World War III promises to be. <br><br>

